count = sum of val[i] = sum of (baseVal[i] ^ lo_flip[i] ^ hi_flip[i])\n\n  // For a given f_lo, define adjusted[i] = baseVal[i] ^ lo_flip[i]\n  // Then count = sum of (adjusted[i] ^ hi_flip[i])\n  //            = sum of adjusted[i] + sum of hi_flip[i] - 2 * sum of (adjusted[i] & hi_flip[i])\n  // No wait, XOR in {0,1}: a^b = a+b - 2ab. So sum of (a^b) = sum(a) + sum(b) - 2*sum(a*b).\n\n  // This is getting complex. Let me use a different MITM approach:\n  // For each button i, it contributes to the \"signature\" based on which half of free vars affects it.\n  // Actually, let me just use a simpler approach: enumerate f_lo, compute a \"state\" vector\n  // that summarizes the effect, then for each f_hi find the best matching state.\n\n  // The \"state\" we care about: for each button, the value before considering f_hi part.\n  // adjusted[i] = baseVal[i] ^ parity(coeff_lo_i & f_lo)\n  // Then final value = adjusted[i] ^ parity(coeff_hi_i & f_hi)\n\n  // Group buttons by coeff_hi value. For buttons with same coeff_hi, they flip together.\n  // The total count = sum over all distinct coeff_hi groups of:\n  //   if group flips (parity(group_coeff_hi & f_hi) = 1): count of 0s in adjusted for this group\n  //   if group doesn't flip: count of 1s in adjusted for this group\n\n  // So the problem reduces to: for each f_lo, compute for each group the counts of 0s and 1s.\n  // Then for f_hi, each group either flips or not, and we want to minimize total.\n  // This is: for each group g with n0_g zeros and n1_g ones in adjusted:\n  //   if flip_g: contributes n0_g, else contributes n1_g\n  //   total = sum over groups of (flip_g ? n0_g : n1_g)\n  //   We want to minimize this. For each group independently, choose the smaller of n0_g, n1_g.\n  // But the flips are determined by f_hi (each bit of f_hi may affect multiple groups).\n  // Actually, group coeff_hi values are half2-bit numbers. Two groups with different coeff_hi\n  // may have different flip patterns.\n\n  // Since h