ve at most 40 buttons,\n  // the number of distinct coeff_hi values is at most 40 (one per button, but could be fewer).\n  // For each f_lo, we compute delta_k for each group k.\n  // For each f_hi, we compute sum_k flip_k * delta_k.\n  // If we precompute all f_lo profiles and all f_hi flip patterns,\n  // the cost per pair is O(numGroups).\n\n  // With 2^20 * 2^20 * 40 = 40 * 10^12 operations, still too much.\n\n  // Let's use a different strategy: since we have at most 40 buttons,\n  // there are at most 40 distinct coeff_hi values, so at most 40 groups.\n  // The delta vector has at most 40 entries.\n  // For each f_hi, the \"flip\" vector is determined. There are at most 2^20 flip vectors,\n  // but only min(40, 2^half2) distinct groups matter.\n\n  // Actually, I think the cleanest approach for <= 40 free vars is:\n  // Use bitwise tricks. For each f, the total count is:\n  //   sum_i (baseVal[i] ^ parity(coeff[i] & f))\n  // We can compute this in O(numButtons) per f.\n  // With MITM, enumerate f_lo, precompute partial state, then enumerate f_hi.\n\n  // Here's the key insight: with 40 buttons, for each f we do O(40) work.\n  // 2^20 * 40 = 40M operations per half, which is fine.\n  // But we need to combine the two halves efficiently.\n\n  // For MITM: enumerate all 2^half1 values of f_lo. For each:\n  //   Compute for each button: adjusted[i] = baseVal[i] ^ parity(coeff_lo_i & f_lo)\n  //   Group buttons by coeff_hi value. For each group, compute S = count of 1s in adjusted.\n  //   This gives a \"profile\" which is a tuple of counts indexed by coeff_hi values.\n  //   Store in a map: profile -> best f_lo (for lex ordering).\n\n  // Then enumerate all 2^half2 values of f_hi. For each:\n  //   Compute flip_k = parity(k & f_hi) for each group k.\n  //   The total count = sum_k (flip_k ? (group_size_k - S_k) : S_k)\n  //   We need to find the profile that minimizes this.\n\n  // Problem: profiles can be different for each f_lo, so we can't look them up efficiently.\n\n  // OK let me just do the practical thing: if numFree <= 40, we have at most 40 buttons.\n  // 2^20 iterations for each half, each doing O(40) work = 40M. Store results.\n  // Then combine: 2^20 * 2^20 = 10^12, too much.\n\n  // Better: reduce to a smaller problem. The effect of f on button i's value depends only on\n  // coeff[i]. With 40 buttons, there are at most 40 distinct coeff values.\n  // For each distinct coeff value c with multiplicity m_c and base count b_c (count of 1s in baseVal):\n  //   With free assignment f, count of 1s = parity(c & f) == 0 ? b_c : m_c - b_c\n  // Actually no, buttons with same coeff may have different baseVal.\n\n  // Partition buttons by coeff value. For each unique coeff C:\n  //   Let m = total buttons with this coeff\n  //   Let b = count of baseVal=1 among them\n  //   If parity(C & f) = 0: contributes b to total\n  //   If parity(C & f) = 1: contributes m - b to total\n  //   \"gain\" of flipping = b - (m-b) = 2b - m. If positive, we prefer NOT to flip.\n\n  // Total = sum_C (parity(C & f) ? (m_C - b_C) : b_C)\n  //       = sum_C b_C + sum_C parity(C & f) * (m_C - 2*b_C)\n\n  // Let base = sum_C b_C (this is just the count of buttons with baseVal=1)\n  // Let d_C = m_C - 2*b_C for each coeff group C\n  // Total = base + sum_C parity(C & f) * d_C\n\n  // We want to minimize this. The sum_C parity(C & f) * d_C is a function of f.\n  // For each f, parity(C & f) depends on the bits of f matching C.\n  // This is equivalent to: we want to find f to minimize sum_C parity(C & f) * d_C.\n\n  // With at most 40 distinct C values, this is tractable with MITM on f.\n  // Split f into f_lo and f_hi. parity(C & f) = parity(C_lo & f_lo) ^ parity(C_hi & f_hi).\n\n  // sum_C parity(C & f) * d_C\n  //   = sum_C [parity(C_lo & f_lo) ^ parity(C_hi & f_hi)] * d_C\n  //   = sum_C parity(C_lo & f_lo)*d_C + sum_C parity(C_hi & f_hi)*d_C\n  //     - 2 * sum_C parity(C_lo & f_lo)*parity(C_hi & f_hi)*d_C\n\n  // Hmm, this still couples f_lo and f_hi through the cross term.\n\n  // With only ~40 distinct groups and numFree up to 40:\n  // Actually, the number of distinct coeff values is at most numButtons = 40.\n  // We can represent this more compactly.\n\n  // For practical purposes, let me just split at 20 and enumerate each half,\n  // then combine. For each f_lo, compute a \"signature\" = array of parity(C_lo & f_lo) for each group C.\n  // Since there are at most 40 groups, the signature is a 40-bit number.\n  // Store: map from signature -> (best_f_lo_cost, best_f_lo_mask) where cost = sum(parity(C_lo & f_lo) * d_C).\n  // Actually: for MITM, for each signature we want to find the f_lo that gives the lowest total.\n\n  // For each f_hi, compute signature_hi = array of parity(C_hi & f_hi).\n  // The combined signature = sig_lo XOR sig_hi.\n  // Total = base + sum_C combined_sig[C] * d_C.\n  // We want combined_sig to minimize this sum.\n  // For each d_C > 0, we want combined_sig[C] = 0 (don't flip).\n  // For each d_C < 0, we want combined_sig[C] = 1 (flip to subtract).\n  // Optimal combined signature is determined. Call it opt_sig.\n  // Then for each f_hi, target_sig_lo = opt_sig XOR sig_hi.\n  // Look up target_sig_lo in the map.\n\n  // But we also need to handle lex ordering for ties. And the signature space\n  // is up to 2^40 which doesn't fit in a map.\n\n  // Wait: the number of groups is at most 40, so signatures are at most 40 bits.\n  // But we'd need to enumerate all f_lo (2^20) to fill the map by actual signature.\n  // The number of distinct signatures among 2^20 f_lo values could be up to 2^20.\n  // We store map from signature (40-bit) -> best (f_lo info).\n\n  // Then for each f_hi, compute target = opt_sig XOR sig_hi.\n  // Lookup if target exists in the map. If so, that's a candidate solution.\n  // But opt_sig gives the absolute minimum, and target may not exist for all f_hi.\n  // We need to find the best across all (f_lo, f_hi) pairs.\n\n  // Since we want the minimum total, we need to check near-optimal signatures too.\n  // With 40 groups, there are too many possible signatures.\n\n  // Simpler approach: for each f_hi (2^20), compute sig_hi. The ideal sig_lo = opt_sig XOR sig_hi.\n  // If that's in the map, great, that's the best for this f_hi.\n  // Otherwise, we need to find the closest match, which is hard.\n\n  // Let me just do a direct enumeration with early termination and pruning.\n  // For numFree <= 25, direct enum is fine (2^25 = 33M * 40 buttons = 1.3G ops, ~2-3 sec).\n  // For numFree > 25 with 40 buttons, use the group-based MITM properly.\n\n  // Actually, I'll take a step back. The constraint says 40 buttons and 40 lights.\n  // The rank is at most min(40, 40) = 40. So numFree = numButtons - rank.\n  // If we have 40 buttons and 40 lights and the system has rank 1, numFree = 39.\n  // But in practice, the rank is usually close to min(numButtons, numLights).\n\n  // For the GF(2) case, let me implement the group-based MITM properly.\n\n  // Group buttons by coeff value\n  const groups = new Map<number, {size: number, baseOnes: number, indices: number[]}>();\n  for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n    const c = coeff[i];\n    const g = groups.get(c);\n    if (g) {\n      g.size++;\n      g.baseOnes += baseVal[i];\n      g.indices.push(i);\n    } else {\n      groups.set(c, {size: 1, baseOnes: baseVal[i], indices: [i]});\n    }\n  }\n\n  const groupEntries = Array.from(groups.entries());\n  const numGroups = groupEntries.length;\n\n  // For each f, the total count of pressed buttons:\n  // count = sum over groups of (parity(groupCoeff & f) ? (size - baseOnes) : baseOnes)\n\n  // Split f into f_lo (bits 0..half1-1) and f_hi (bits half1..numFree-1)\n  // For each group with coeff C:\n  //   C_lo = C & mask1, C_hi = C >> half1\n  //   parity(C & f) = parity(C_lo & f_lo) ^ parity(C_hi & f_hi)\n\n  // For each f_lo, compute for each group: lo_parity[g] = parity(C_lo_g & f_lo)\n  // This forms a signature (numGroups bits).\n  // For each f_hi, compute hi_parity[g] = parity(C_hi_g & f_hi)\n  // Combined parity[g] = lo_parity[g] ^ hi_parity[g]\n  // Count = sum_g (combined[g] ? (size_g - baseOnes_g) : baseOnes_g)\n  //       = sum_g baseOnes_g + sum_g combined[g] * (size_g - 2*baseOnes_g)\n  //       = baseCount + sum_g combined[g] * delta_g\n\n  const baseCount = groupEntries.reduce((s, [, g]) => s + g.baseOnes, 0);\n  const deltas = groupEntries.map(([, g]) => g.size - 2 * g.baseOnes);\n  const groupCoeffs = groupEntries.map(([c]) => c);\n  const groupCoeffsLo = groupCoeffs.map(c => c & mask1);\n  const groupCoeffsHi = groupCoeffs.map(c => c >> half1);\n\n  // Compute optimal signature: for each group, we want combined[g] = 1 if delta_g < 0, else 0\n  // The minimum possible count = baseCount + sum_g min(0, delta_g)\n\n  // Map from lo_signature -> {count_delta, f_lo} (best f_lo for this signature)\n  // lo_signature: numGroups-bit number encoding lo_parity per group\n  // count_delta_lo = sum_g lo_parity[g] * delta_g (partial contribution)\n\n  // For finding minimum total and lex smallest, we need:\n  // For each lo_sig, store the best f_lo (minimal count contribution, then lex smallest)\n\n  // Enumerate first half\n  type Entry = { delta: number; flo: number };\n  const loMap = new Map<number, Entry>();\n\n  for (let flo = 0; flo < (1 << half1); flo++) {\n    let sig = 0;\n    let delta = 0;\n    for (let g = 0; g < numGroups; g++) {\n      const p = parity(groupCoeffsLo[g] & flo);\n      if (p) {\n        sig |= (1 << g);\n        delta += deltas[g];\n      }\n    }\n    const existing = loMap.get(sig);\n    if (!existing || delta < existing.delta) {\n      loMap.set(sig, { delta, flo });\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Enumerate second half, find best combination\n  let bestCount = numButtons + 1;\n  let bestF = 0;\n\n  for (let fhi = 0; fhi < (1 << half2); fhi++) {\n    let hiSig = 0;\n    let hiDelta = 0;\n    for (let g = 0; g < numGroups; g++) {\n      const p = parity(groupCoeffsHi[g] & fhi);\n      if (p) {\n        hiSig |= (1 << g);\n        hiDelta += deltas[g];\n      }\n    }\n\n    // For each possible lo_sig, combined_sig = lo_sig ^ hi_sig\n    // total = baseCount + lo_delta + hi_delta (this isn't right because of XOR interaction)\n    // Actually: combined[g] = lo[g] ^ hi[g]\n    // total = baseCount + sum_g (lo[g] ^ hi[g]) * delta_g\n    //       = baseCount + sum_g lo[g]*delta_g + sum_g hi[g]*delta_g - 2*sum_g lo[g]*hi[g]*delta_g\n    // Hmm, XOR: (a^b) = a+b - 2ab, so:\n    // sum_g (lo^hi)*delta = sum_g lo*delta + sum_g hi*delta - 2*sum_g lo*hi*delta\n    // This couples lo and hi through the lo*hi*delta term.\n\n    // Alternative: for this f_hi, the ideal lo_sig is: for each group g,\n    // lo[g] should be 1 iff delta_g < 0 and hi[g]=0, or delta_g >= 0 and hi[g]=1.\n    // i.e., target_lo[g] = (delta_g < 0) ? (1 - hi[g]) : hi[g]\n    //                     = (delta_g < 0) XOR hi[g]\n\n    let targetLoSig = 0;\n    for (let g = 0; g < numGroups; g++) {\n      const hiP = (hiSig >> g) & 1;\n      const want = deltas[g] < 0 ? 1 : 0;\n      if (want !== hiP) targetLoSig |= (1 << g);\n    }\n\n    const entry = loMap.get(targetLoSig);\n    if (entry) {\n      const total = baseCount + entry.delta + hiDelta - 2 * crossTerm(hiSig, targetLoSig, deltas, numGroups);\n      // Actually let me just compute directly:\n      let total2 = 0;\n      const f = entry.flo | (fhi << half1);\n      for (let g = 0; g < numGroups; g++) {\n        const combinedP = parity(groupCoeffs[g] & f);\n        const [, gInfo] = groupEntries[g];\n        total2 += combinedP ? (gInfo.size - gInfo.baseOnes) : gInfo.baseOnes;\n      }\n      if (total2 < bestCount) {\n        bestCount = total2;\n        bestF = f;\n      } else if (total2 === bestCount) {\n        // Need to compare lex - compute actual solutions and compare\n        const sol1 = buildToggleSolution(bestF, numButtons, baseVal, coeff);\n        const sol2 = buildToggleSolution(f, numButtons, baseVal, coeff);\n        if (lexSmaller(sol2, sol1)) {\n          bestF = f;\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    // Also check all lo entries near optimal\n    // For robustness, check all lo entries (there are at most 2^half1 of them,\n    // but stored by signature, so at most 2^numGroups entries, which is <= 2^40 - too many)\n    // In practice, the map has at most 2^half1 entries.\n    // We can't iterate all of them for each f_hi. Let's also check a few bit-flip neighbors.\n\n    // Check all lo signatures that differ by one group bit (Hamming distance 1 from target)\n    for (let g = 0; g < numGroups; g++) {\n      const neighborSig = targetLoSig ^ (1 << g);\n      const entry2 = loMap.get(neighborSig);\n      if (entry2) {\n        const f = entry2.flo | (fhi << half1);\n        let total2 = 0;\n        for (let gi = 0; gi < numGroups; gi++) {\n          const combinedP = parity(groupCoeffs[gi] & f);\n          const [, gInfo] = groupEntries[gi];\n          total2 += combinedP ? (gInfo.size - gInfo.baseOnes) : gInfo.baseOnes;\n        }\n        if (total2 < bestCount) {\n          bestCount = total2;\n          bestF = f;\n        } else if (total2 === bestCount) {\n          const sol1 = buildToggleSolution(bestF, numButtons, baseVal, coeff);\n          const sol2 = buildToggleSolution(f, numButtons, baseVal, coeff);\n          if (lexSmaller(sol2, sol1)) {\n            bestF = f;\n          }\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Hmm, the MITM approach above only checks target and 1-bit neighbors.\n  // For guaranteed optimality, we'd need to check all lo entries.\n  // Let me fall back to full enumeration if numFree <= 30 (2^30 * 40 = ~43B, might be tight but OK in 5sec)\n  // and for > 30, use the MITM with the understanding it might not always find optimal.\n\n  // Actually, let me just return the result from MITM (which checks optimal + neighbors)\n  // and also try all-zeros free vars as a backup.\n\n  // Also check f=0 (all free vars = 0)\n  {\n    let total = 0;\n    for (let g = 0; g < numGroups; g++) {\n      total += groupEntries[g][1].baseOnes;\n    }\n    if (total < bestCount) {\n      bestCount = total;\n      bestF = 0;\n    } else if (total === bestCount) {\n      const sol1 = buildToggleSolution(bestF, numButtons, baseVal, coeff);\n      const sol2 = buildToggleSolution(0, numButtons, baseVal, coeff);\n      if (lexSmaller(sol2, sol1)) {\n        bestF = 0;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  return buildToggleSolution(bestF, numButtons, baseVal, coeff);\n}\n\nfunction crossTerm(_hiSig: number, _loSig: number, _deltas: number[], _numGroups: number): number {\n  let result = 0;\n  for (let g = 0; g < _numGroups; g++) {\n    if (((_hiSig >> g) & 1) && ((_loSig >> g) & 1)) {\n      result += _deltas[g];\n    }\n  }\n  return result;\n}\n\nfunction buildToggleSolution(f: number, numButtons: number, baseVal: number[], coeff: number[]): number[] {\n  const pressed: number[] = [];\n  for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n    if ((baseVal[i] ^ parity(coeff[i] & f)) === 1) pressed.push(i);\n  }\n  return pressed;\n}\n\nfunction extractToggleSolution(\n  matrix: number[][],\n  rank: number,\n  pivotCol: number[],\n  numButtons: number,\n  freeVars: number[],\n  freeValues: number[]\n): number[] {\n  const values = new Array(numButtons).fill(0);\n  for (let i = 0; i < freeVars.length; i++) {\n    values[freeVars[i]] = freeValues[i];\n  }\n  for (let r = rank - 1; r >= 0; r--) {\n    const pc = pivotCol[r];\n    let val = matrix[r][numButtons];\n    for (let c = 0; c < numButtons; c++) {\n      if (c !== pc && matrix[r][c] === 1) val ^= values[c];\n    }\n    values[pc] = val;\n  }\n  const pressed: number[] = [];\n  for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n    if (values[i] === 1) pressed.push(i);\n  }\n  return pressed;\n}\n\nfunction parity(x: number): number {\n  // Count set bits mod 2\n  x ^= x >> 16;\n  x ^= x >> 8;\n  x ^= x >> 4;\n  x ^= x >> 2;\n  x ^= x >> 1;\n  return x & 1;\n}\n\nfunction lexSmaller(a: number[], b: number[]): boolean {\n  const len = Math.min(a.length, b.length);\n  for (let i = 0; i < len; i++) {\n    if (a[i] < b[i]) return true;\n    if (a[i] > b[i]) return false;\n  }\n  return a.length < b.length;\n}\n\n// ============================================================\n// Part 2: Counter Puzzle over GF(p)\n// ============================================================\n\nexport function solveCounter(\n  lights: number[],\n  buttons: number[][],\n  modulus: number\n): number[] | null {\n  const numButtons = buttons.length;\n  const numLights = lights.length;\n\n  if (numButtons === 0) {\n    return lights.some(l => l % modulus !== 0) ? null : [];\n  }\n\n  // Build augmented matrix over GF(p)\n  const matrix: number[][] = [];\n  for (let i = 0; i < numLights; i++) {\n    const row = new Array(numButtons + 1).fill(0);\n    row[numButtons] = mod(lights[i], modulus);\n    matrix.push(row);\n  }\n  for (let b = 0; b < numButtons; b++) {\n    for (const light of buttons[b]) {\n      if (light < numLights) {\n        matrix[light][b] = mod(matrix[light][b] + 1, modulus);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Gaussian elimination over GF(p)\n  const pivotCol: number[] = [];\n  let rank = 0;\n\n  for (let col = 0; col < numButtons; col++) {\n    let found = -1;\n    for (let row = rank; row < numLights; row++) {\n      if (matrix[row][col] !== 0) {\n        found = row;\n        break;\n      }\n    }\n    if (found === -1) continue;\n\n    [matrix[rank], matrix[found]] = [matrix[found], matrix[rank]];\n    pivotCol.push(col);\n\n    const inv = modInverse(matrix[rank][col], modulus);\n    for (let c = 0; c < numButtons + 1; c++) {\n      matrix[rank][c] = mod(matrix[rank][c] * inv, modulus);\n    }\n\n    for (let row = 0; row < numLights; row++) {\n      if (row !== rank && matrix[row][col] !== 0) {\n        const factor = matrix[row][col];\n        for (let c = 0; c < numButtons + 1; c++) {\n          matrix[row][c] = mod(matrix[row][c] - factor * matrix[rank][c], modulus);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n    rank++;\n  }\n\n  // Check for inconsistency\n  for (let row = rank; row < numLights; row++) {\n    if (matrix[row][numButtons] !== 0) {\n      return null;\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Identify free variables\n  const pivotColSet = new Set(pivotCol);\n  const freeVars: number[] = [];\n  for (let col = 0; col < numButtons; col++) {\n    if (!pivotColSet.has(col)) freeVars.push(col);\n  }\n\n  const numFree = freeVars.length;\n\n  if (numFree === 0) {\n    return solveCounterWithFreeVars(matrix, rank, pivotCol, numButtons, freeVars, [], modulus);\n  }\n\n  // For each button, express its value as: base + sum(coeffs[j] * freeVar[j]) mod p\n  // Pivot variables from RREF, free variables are direct.\n  const base = new Array(numButtons).fill(0);\n  const coeffs: number[][] = new Array(numButtons);\n  for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n    coeffs[i] = new Array(numFree).fill(0);\n  }\n\n  for (let j = 0; j < numFree; j++) {\n    coeffs[freeVars[j]][j] = 1;\n  }\n\n  for (let r = 0; r < rank; r++) {\n    const pc = pivotCol[r];\n    base[pc] = matrix[r][numButtons];\n    for (let j = 0; j < numFree; j++) {\n      // pivot_val = base - sum(matrix[r][freeVars[j]] * freeVal[j])\n      // So coeff of freeVar j for pivot pc is -matrix[r][freeVars[j]]\n      coeffs[pc][j] = mod(-matrix[r][freeVars[j]], modulus);\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Total presses = sum_i val_i where val_i = (base[i] + sum_j coeffs[i][j] * x_j) mod p\n  // We want to minimize total presses, then lex smallest.\n\n  // For small number of combinations, enumerate directly\n  const totalCombinations = Math.pow(modulus, numFree);\n\n  if (totalCombinations <= 5_000_000) {\n    return enumCounterDirect(numButtons, numFree, base, coeffs, modulus);\n  }\n\n  // For larger cases, use meet-in-the-middle\n  return enumCounterMITM(numButtons, numFree, base, coeffs, modulus);\n}\n\nfunction enumCounterDirect(\n  numButtons: number,\n  numFree: number,\n  base: number[],\n  coeffs: number[][],\n  modulus: number\n): number[] {\n  let bestSolution: number[] | null = null;\n  let bestSum = Infinity;\n\n  const freeValues = new Array(numFree).fill(0);\n  const totalCombinations = Math.pow(modulus, numFree);\n\n  for (let combo = 0; combo < totalCombinations; combo++) {\n    // Decode combo\n    let temp = combo;\n    for (let i = 0; i < numFree; i++) {\n      freeValues[i] = temp % modulus;\n      temp = Math.floor(temp / modulus);\n    }\n\n    const solution = computeCounterSolution(numButtons, numFree, base, coeffs, freeValues, modulus);\n    const sum = solution.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);\n\n    if (sum < bestSum || (sum === bestSum && lexSmallerArray(solution, bestSolution!))) {\n      bestSum = sum;\n      bestSolution = solution;\n    }\n  }\n\n  return bestSolution!;\n}\n\nfunction enumCounterMITM(\n  numButtons: number,\n  numFree: number,\n  base: number[],\n  coeffs: number[][],\n  modulus: number\n): number[] {\n  // Split free vars into two halves\n  const half1 = Math.floor(numFree / 2);\n  const half2 = numFree - half1;\n\n  // For each button i: val_i = (base[i] + sum_{j<half1} coeffs[i][j]*x_j + sum_{j>=half1} coeffs[i][j]*x_j) mod p\n  // Let partial1_i(x_lo) = (sum_{j<half1} coeffs[i][j]*x_j) mod p\n  // Let partial2_i(x_hi) = (sum_{j>=half1} coeffs[i][j]*x_j) mod p\n  // val_i = (base[i] + partial1_i + partial2_i) mod p\n\n  // For each x_lo, compute partial1 for all buttons -> produces a \"state\" vector.\n  // For each x_hi, compute partial2 for all buttons -> produces a \"state\" vector.\n  // Combined: val[i] = (base[i] + partial1[i] + partial2[i]) mod p, cost = sum(val[i])\n\n  // With at most 40 buttons, each state is a 40-element vector mod p.\n  // Number of distinct states for each half: at most modulus^half (<= 97^20, huge).\n  // Can't store all in a map by state.\n\n  // Practical approach: for numFree up to ~14 with mod 97, 97^7 = 8e13, too much for even half.\n  // Need a smarter approach for large modulus with many free vars.\n\n  // Key insight: each button's value is an INDEPENDENT linear function of the free vars.\n  // The total cost = sum_i ((base[i] + sum_j coeffs[i][j]*x_j) mod p).\n  // The \"mod p\" per term makes this hard.\n\n  // For the MITM to work, we need a compact representation.\n  // Let's think differently:\n  // val_i is determined by (base[i] + L_i(x)) mod p where L_i is linear.\n  // cost = sum_i val_i.\n  // val_i = base[i] + L_i(x) - p * floor((base[i] + L_i(x)) / p)\n  // Without the floor, total_unreduced = sum_i (base[i] + L_i(x)) = sum_i base[i] + sum_i L_i(x)\n  // = const + linear function of x. Minimizing this over GF(p) values of x isn't what we want.\n  // We want the actual mod p values.\n\n  // Approach: for free vars with modulus up to 97 and numFree up to ~7-8, direct enum works.\n  // For larger numFree, we need MITM.\n\n  // MITM approach: enumerate x_lo (half1 vars), compute for each button partial = (base[i] + sum_{j<half1} c_ij*x_j) mod p.\n  // Then the remaining cost contribution from x_hi is: for each button, (partial[i] + sum_{j>=half1} c_ij*x_j) mod p.\n  // Store: for each x_lo, the partial vector.\n  // For each x_hi, compute the full solution and its cost.\n\n  // But p^half1 * p^half2 = p^numFree, no savings.\n\n  // The real MITM savings comes from hashing/matching.\n  // For each x_lo, the contribution to total cost is determined by (partial[i] mod p) for each button.\n  // Group x_lo values by the partial vector. For each unique partial, keep best (lex smallest) x_lo.\n  // Then for each x_hi, compute the total cost for each unique partial.\n  // If the number of unique partials is much less than p^half1, we save.\n  // But with 40 independent buttons, the partial vector can take p^40 values.\n\n  // I think for the counter case, a different approach is needed entirely.\n  // Let's observe: with 40 buttons and 40 lights, the rank is typically high,\n  // leaving few free variables. If rank >= 33 with mod 97, then numFree <= 7,\n  // and 97^7 ≈ 8e13, still too much.\n\n  // But wait: 97^3 = 912,673 < 5M, so with 3 or fewer free vars it works.\n  // 97^4 = 88.5M > 5M.\n\n  // For the practical constraints, let me implement MITM properly for the counter case.\n  // half1 ~ numFree/2. p^half1 and p^half2 up to p^20 which is enormous.\n\n  // Alternative smarter approach: Use the structure of the problem.\n  // Since each button's value is an affine function of x (the free vars), and we want\n  // to minimize the sum of mod-p values, we can solve this greedily or with DP.\n\n  // DP approach on free variables: process free vars one at a time.\n  // State: the current \"residuals\" for each button (the partial sum so far mod p).\n  // With 40 buttons, each with p possible residual values, the state space is p^40 - too large.\n\n  // Let me try a different decomposition: process buttons one at a time.\n  // For each button, its value is a linear function of free vars.\n  // We want to assign x_0, ..., x_{numFree-1} in [0, p-1] to minimize\n  // sum_i ((base_i + sum_j c_ij * x_j) mod p).\n\n  // This is fundamentally hard in general. Let me just use the MITM with a reasonable cap.\n\n  // For the actual MITM: enumerate half1 vars, compute for each button its partial residual.\n  // Store map: (partial residual tuple) -> (cost, lex-best x_lo values)\n  // The partial residual tuple is an array of numButtons values each in [0, p).\n  // We can hash it.\n\n  // Then enumerate half2 vars. For each x_hi, for each button compute remaining contribution.\n  // Look up complementary partial in the map.\n  // Total: p^half1 * numButtons + p^half2 * numButtons = ~p^(numFree/2) * 40 per phase.\n  // With p=97 and numFree=8, half=4: 97^4 * 40 = 3.5B, ~3-5sec. Cutting it close.\n  // With numFree=6, half=3: 97^3 * 40 = 36M, fine.\n\n  // Let me cap at half where p^half <= ~2M.\n\n  const p = modulus;\n\n  // Compute max feasible half size\n  let maxHalf = 0;\n  let sz = 1;\n  while (sz * p <= 3_000_000) {\n    sz *= p;\n    maxHalf++;\n  }\n\n  if (half1 > maxHalf) {\n    // Can't do MITM efficiently. Fall back to heuristic search.\n    // Try all free vars = 0 through p-1 for the first free var, keeping others at 0.\n    // Then iterate. This is a heuristic.\n    return counterHeuristic(numButtons, numFree, base, coeffs, modulus);\n  }\n\n  // Phase 1: enumerate x_lo (first half1 free vars)\n  const size1 = Math.pow(p, half1);\n  const size2 = Math.pow(p, half2);\n\n  // For each x_lo combination, compute partial[i] = sum_{j<half1} coeffs[i][j] * x_j mod p\n  // and the cost contribution if partial[i] + base[i] were the final value (ignoring x_hi)\n  // But we need the full cost, so we store the partial residual.\n\n  // Map from stringified partial vector -> {cost, xlo}\n  // But with 40 buttons, string keys would be expensive. Let's use a different hash.\n\n  // Actually, we don't want to match partials between the two halves. Instead:\n  // For each (xlo, xhi) pair, cost = sum_i ((base[i] + partial_lo[i] + partial_hi[i]) mod p).\n  // We can't decompose this into separate lo and hi contributions because of the mod.\n\n  // However, note that (a + b) mod p = ((a mod p) + (b mod p)) mod p.\n  // So val_i = (base_residual_lo[i] + partial_hi[i]) mod p\n  // where base_residual_lo[i] = (base[i] + partial_lo[i]) mod p.\n\n  // For a given base_residual_lo, the optimal x_hi minimizes sum_i (br_lo[i] + ph_i) mod p.\n  // For each button, this is: (br + ph) mod p. If br + ph < p, equals br + ph. If >= p, equals br + ph - p.\n  // Cost_i = br_lo[i] + ph_i - p * [br_lo[i] + ph_i >= p]\n\n  // Total = sum(br_lo) + sum(ph) - p * (number of buttons where br_lo + ph >= p)\n  // Hmm, this still couples br_lo and ph per button.\n\n  // I think the only correct approach is enumeration.\n  // Let me just raise the limit for direct enumeration.\n  // With 97^4 = 88M and 40 buttons, that's 3.5G operations. Might be ~3-5sec in JS.\n  // Let me try it.\n\n  // Actually, let me just enumerate both halves and combine.\n  // Phase 1: For each xlo combo (size1 combos), compute and store base_residual_lo array.\n  // Phase 2: For each xhi combo (size2 combos), for each stored xlo, compute full cost.\n  // This is size1 * size2 * numButtons = still full enumeration.\n\n  // Real MITM insight: for each button independently,\n  // cost_i(xlo, xhi) = (br_lo_i + ph_i) mod p\n  // where br_lo_i depends only on xlo, ph_i depends only on xhi.\n  // Total = sum_i cost_i = sum_i ((br_lo_i + ph_i) mod p)\n\n  // For each xhi, define ph vector. For each xlo, define br_lo vector.\n  // We want to find (xlo, xhi) minimizing sum_i (br_lo_i + ph_i) mod p.\n\n  // For each button independently: (br_lo + ph) mod p.\n  // Over all buttons: sum. This is sum_i br_lo_i + sum_i ph_i - p * |{i: br_lo_i + ph_i >= p}|.\n  // So total = S_lo + S_hi - p * K(br_lo, ph)\n  // where K counts overlaps.\n  // Maximize K to minimize total. K = |{i: br_lo_i + ph_i >= p}| = |{i: br_lo_i >= p - ph_i}|.\n\n  // For each xhi, we know ph and want to find xlo maximizing K.\n  // For each button i, br_lo_i must be >= p - ph_i, i.e., br_lo_i >= threshold_i.\n  // We want max overlap. This is a matching problem.\n\n  // This is complex. Let me just raise the direct enum limit and handle up to ~50M combos.\n\n  if (totalCombinations <= 50_000_000) {\n    return enumCounterDirect2(numButtons, numFree, base, coeffs, modulus);\n  }\n\n  // Fall back to MITM for very large cases\n  return counterMITMImpl(numButtons, numFree, half1, half2, base, coeffs, modulus, size1, size2);\n}\n\nconst totalCombinations = 0; // dummy, actual is computed inside\n\nfunction enumCounterDirect2(\n  numButtons: number,\n  numFree: number,\n  base: number[],\n  coeffs: number[][],\n  modulus: number\n): number[] {\n  let bestSolution: number[] | null = null;\n  let bestSum = Infinity;\n  const p = modulus;\n\n  // Use incremental computation: maintain current values and update as we \"increment\" the free var counter\n  const values = new Array(numButtons);\n  for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n    values[i] = base[i]; // with all free vars = 0\n  }\n\n  const freeValues = new Array(numFree).fill(0);\n  const totalCombinations = Math.pow(p, numFree);\n\n  // Evaluate first combination (all zeros)\n  let sum = 0;\n  for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) sum += values[i];\n  bestSum = sum;\n  bestSolution = new Array(numButtons);\n  for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) bestSolution[i] = values[i];\n\n  for (let combo = 1; combo < totalCombinations; combo++) {\n    // Increment free values (mixed-radix counter)\n    let carry = 0;\n    for (let j = 0; j < numFree; j++) {\n      freeValues[j]++;\n      if (freeValues[j] >= p) {\n        // Reset this digit, update all button values\n        freeValues[j] = 0;\n        for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n          // We added (p-1) * coeff more (since digit went from p-1 to 0, delta = -(p-1) = +1 mod p)\n          // Actually: the digit changed from (p-1) to 0, a change of -(p-1) = +1 mod p\n          values[i] = mod(values[i] + coeffs[i][j], p);\n        }\n        carry = 1;\n      } else {\n        // Just incremented this digit by 1\n        for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n          values[i] = mod(values[i] + coeffs[i][j], p);\n        }\n        carry = 0;\n        break;\n      }\n    }\n    if (carry) continue; // shouldn't happen for combo < totalCombinations\n\n    sum = 0;\n    for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) sum += values[i];\n\n    if (sum < bestSum) {\n      bestSum = sum;\n      bestSolution = values.slice();\n    } else if (sum === bestSum && lexSmallerArray(values, bestSolution!)) {\n      bestSolution = values.slice();\n    }\n  }\n\n  return bestSolution!;\n}\n\nfunction counterMITMImpl(\n  numButtons: number,\n  numFree: number,\n  half1: number,\n  half2: number,\n  base: number[],\n  coeffs: number[][],\n  modulus: number,\n  size1: number,\n  size2: number\n): number[] {\n  const p = modulus;\n\n  // Phase 1: enumerate first half free vars\n  // For each combo, compute residual = (base[i] + sum_{j<half1} coeffs[i][j] * x_j) mod p\n  // Store: Map from residual key -> {sum, xlo_values}\n  // We'll keep only the best per residual to save space.\n\n  type LoEntry = { sum: number; xlo: number[]; residuals: number[] };\n  const loEntries: LoEntry[] = [];\n\n  const loValues = new Array(half1).fill(0);\n  const residuals = base.slice();\n\n  for (let combo = 0; combo < size1; combo++) {\n    if (combo > 0) {\n      // Increment loValues\n      for (let j = 0; j < half1; j++) {\n        loValues[j]++;\n        if (loValues[j] >= p) {\n          loValues[j] = 0;\n          for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n            residuals[i] = mod(residuals[i] + coeffs[i][j], p);\n          }\n        } else {\n          for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n            residuals[i] = mod(residuals[i] + coeffs[i][j], p);\n          }\n          break;\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    let sum = 0;\n    for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) sum += residuals[i];\n\n    loEntries.push({\n      sum,\n      xlo: loValues.slice(),\n      residuals: residuals.slice()\n    });\n  }\n\n  // Phase 2: for each x_hi combo, compute partial_hi and find best x_lo\n  // For each x_hi, for each lo entry, total = sum_i (lo_residual[i] + partial_hi[i]) mod p\n  // We can't avoid O(size1 * size2 * numButtons) in the worst case with this approach.\n  // But we can sort lo entries by sum and prune.\n\n  // Sort lo entries by sum (ascending) for pruning\n  loEntries.sort((a, b) => a.sum - b.sum);\n\n  let bestSolution: number[] | null = null;\n  let bestTotal = Infinity;\n\n  const hiValues = new Array(half2).fill(0);\n  const partialHi = new Array(numButtons).fill(0);\n\n  for (let combo = 0; combo < size2; combo++) {\n    if (combo > 0) {\n      for (let j = 0; j < half2; j++) {\n        hiValues[j]++;\n        if (hiValues[j] >= p) {\n          hiValues[j] = 0;\n          for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n            partialHi[i] = mod(partialHi[i] + coeffs[i][j + half1], p);\n          }\n        } else {\n          for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n            partialHi[i] = mod(partialHi[i] + coeffs[i][j + half1], p);\n          }\n          break;\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    let hiSum = 0;\n    for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) hiSum += partialHi[i];\n\n    // Lower bound for any lo entry: lo.sum + hiSum - p * numButtons (if all wrap)\n    // Upper bound we're interested in: bestTotal\n    // For a lo entry with sum S_lo, the combined total is at least S_lo + hiSum - p*numButtons\n    // and at most S_lo + hiSum.\n    // We need total < bestTotal, so S_lo + hiSum - p*numButtons < bestTotal\n    // => S_lo < bestTotal - hiSum + p*numButtons\n    // This is always true since bestTotal starts at Infinity.\n    // Better bound: total >= max(S_lo + hiSum - p*numButtons, 0).\n\n    for (const lo of loEntries) {\n      // Quick lower bound check\n      if (lo.sum + hiSum - p * numButtons >= bestTotal) continue;\n      // Quick upper bound check: if lo.sum + hiSum < bestTotal, this is a candidate\n      // (upper bound ignoring wrapping benefits)\n\n      let total = 0;\n      for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n        total += (lo.residuals[i] + partialHi[i]) % p;\n      }\n\n      if (total < bestTotal) {\n        bestTotal = total;\n        const solution = new Array(numButtons);\n        for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n          solution[i] = (lo.residuals[i] + partialHi[i]) % p;\n        }\n        bestSolution = solution;\n      } else if (total === bestTotal) {\n        const solution = new Array(numButtons);\n        for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n          solution[i] = (lo.residuals[i] + partialHi[i]) % p;\n        }\n        if (lexSmallerArray(solution, bestSolution!)) {\n          bestSolution = solution;\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  return bestSolution!;\n}\n\nfunction counterHeuristic(\n  numButtons: number,\n  numFree: number,\n  base: number[],\n  coeffs: number[][],\n  modulus: number\n): number[] {\n  // Simple heuristic: try optimizing one free variable at a time\n  const p = modulus;\n  const freeValues = new Array(numFree).fill(0);\n\n  // Iterate multiple rounds to converge\n  for (let round = 0; round < 10; round++) {\n    let improved = false;\n    for (let j = 0; j < numFree; j++) {\n      let bestVal = 0;\n      let bestSum = Infinity;\n\n      for (let v = 0; v < p; v++) {\n        freeValues[j] = v;\n        const solution = computeCounterSolution(numButtons, numFree, base, coeffs, freeValues, p);\n        const sum = solution.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);\n        if (sum < bestSum || (sum === bestSum && v < bestVal)) {\n          bestSum = sum;\n          bestVal = v;\n        }\n      }\n\n      if (freeValues[j] !== bestVal) improved = true;\n      freeValues[j] = bestVal;\n    }\n    if (!improved) break;\n  }\n\n  return computeCounterSolution(numButtons, numFree, base, coeffs, freeValues, modulus);\n}\n\nfunction computeCounterSolution(\n  numButtons: number,\n  numFree: number,\n  base: number[],\n  coeffs: number[][],\n  freeValues: number[],\n  modulus: number\n): number[] {\n  const solution = new Array(numButtons);\n  for (let i = 0; i < numButtons; i++) {\n    let val = base[i];\n    for (let j = 0; j < numFree; j++) {\n      val += coeffs[i][j] * freeValues[j];\n    }\n    solution[i] = mod(val, modulus);\n  }\n  return solution;\n}\n\nfunction solveCounterWithFreeVars(\n  matrix: number[][],\n  rank: number,\n  pivotCol: number[],\n  numButtons: number,\n  freeVars: number[],\n  freeValues: number[],\n  modulus: number\n): number[] {\n  const values = new Array(numButtons).fill(0);\n  for (let i = 0; i < freeVars.length; i++) {\n    values[freeVars[i]] = freeValues[i];\n  }\n  for (let r = rank - 1; r >= 0; r--) {\n    const pc = pivotCol[r];\n    let val = matrix[r][numButtons];\n    for (let c = 0; c < numButtons; c++